   Recommendation 4: SQL Tuning
   Estimated benefit is .27 active sessions, 4.65% of total activity.

      "bbwhryws27hzv".
      Related Object
         SQL statement with SQL_ID bbwhryws27hzv.
         SELECT min(k1.autodat), k1.did, max(k1.arbeitstag) from 
         val_kal_vid k1
         inner join (select autodat, did, arbeitstag -- 
         autodat-TO_DATE('14.02.2014','dd.mm.yyyy'), arbeitstag
         from val_kal_vid
         where autodat>=TO_DATE('14.02.2014','dd.mm.yyyy')
         and autodat<=TO_DATE('31.12.9999','dd.mm.yyyy')
         and to_date(to_char(autodat,'yyyymmdd')||'110000','yyyymmddhh24miss')
         >sysdate
         and autodat<=to_date('31.12.2021','dd.mm.yyyy') and 
         mod((to_number(to_char(autodat,'yyyy'))*12+to_number(to_char(autodat,
         'mm')))- 024170,01)=0 and autodat in (select k1.autodat
         from val_kal_vid k1 left join val_kal_vid k2 on 
         to_char(k1.autodat,'yyyymm')=to_char(k2.autodat,'yyyymm') and 
         k1.autodat>=k2.autodat and k1.wd=k2.wd 
         where k1.wd=1
         group by k1.autodat
         having count(k2.wd)=1) ) pre on k1.did=pre.did+(1-pre.arbeitstag)
         where to_date(to_char(k1.autodat,'yyyymmdd')||'110000','yyyymmddhh24m
         iss')>sysdate
         group by k1.did
         order by min(k1.autodat)

Finding 2: CPU Usage
Impact is .74 active sessions, 12.81% of total activity.
--------------------------------------------------------
Host CPU was a bottleneck and the instance was consuming 80% of the host CPU. 
All wait times will be inflated by wait for CPU.
Host CPU consumption was 80%.
 
   Recommendation 1: Application Analysis
   Estimated benefit is 5.13 active sessions, 88.42% of total activity.
   --------------------------------------------------------------------
   Action
      Look at the "Top SQL Statements" finding for SQL statements consuming 
      significant time on CPU. For example, the SELECT statement with SQL_ID 
      "a9n705a9gfb71" is responsible for 11% of CPU usage during the analysis 
      period.
 
   Recommendation 2: Host Configuration
   Estimated benefit is .74 active sessions, 12.81% of total activity.
   -------------------------------------------------------------------
   Action
      Consider adding more CPUs to the host or adding instances serving the 
      database on other hosts.
   Action
      Session CPU consumption was throttled by the Oracle Resource Manager. 
      Consider revising the resource plan that was active during the analysis 
      period.
 
 
Finding 3: "User I/O" wait Class
Impact is .5 active sessions, 8.57% of total activity.
------------------------------------------------------
Wait class "User I/O" was consuming significant database time.
Waits for I/O to temporary tablespaces were not consuming significant database 
time.
The throughput of the I/O subsystem was not significantly lower than expected.
 
   No recommendations are available.
 
 
Finding 4: Session Connect and Disconnect
Impact is .21 active sessions, 3.56% of total activity.
-------------------------------------------------------
Session connect and disconnect calls were consuming significant database time.
 
   Recommendation 1: Application Analysis
   Estimated benefit is .21 active sessions, 3.56% of total activity.
   ------------------------------------------------------------------
   Action
      Investigate application logic for possible reduction of connect and 
      disconnect calls. For example, you might use a connection pool scheme in 
      the middle tier.
 
 
Finding 5: Undersized SGA
Impact is .14 active sessions, 2.44% of total activity.
-------------------------------------------------------
The SGA was inadequately sized, causing additional I/O or hard parses.
The value of parameter "sga_target" was "20480 M" during the analysis period.
 
   Recommendation 1: Database Configuration
   Estimated benefit is .12 active sessions, 2.11% of total activity.
   ------------------------------------------------------------------
   Action
      Increase the size of the SGA by setting the parameter "sga_target" to 
      23040 M.
 
   Symptoms That Led to the Finding:
   ---------------------------------
      Wait class "User I/O" was consuming significant database time.

         inner join (select autodat, did, arbeitstag -- 
         autodat-TO_DATE('14.02.2014','dd.mm.yyyy'), arbeitstag
         from val_kal_vid
         where autodat>=TO_DATE('14.02.2014','dd.mm.yyyy')
         and autodat<=TO_DATE('31.12.9999','dd.mm.yyyy')
         and to_date(to_char(autodat,'yyyymmdd')||'092000','yyyymmddhh24miss')
         >sysdate
         and autodat<=to_date('31.12.2021','dd.mm.yyyy') and 
         mod((to_number(to_char(autodat,'yyyy'))*12+to_number(to_char(autodat,
         'mm')))- 024170,01)=0 and autodat in (select k1.autodat
         from val_kal_vid k1 left join val_kal_vid k2 on 
         to_char(k1.autodat,'yyyymm')=to_char(k2.autodat,'yyyymm') and 
         k1.autodat>=k2.autodat and k1.wd=k2.wd 
         where k1.wd=1
         group by k1.autodat
         having count(k2.wd)=1) ) pre on k1.did=pre.did+(1-pre.arbeitstag)
         where to_date(to_char(k1.autodat,'yyyymmdd')||'092000','yyyymmddhh24m
         iss')>sysdate
         group by k1.did
         order by min(k1.autodat)
   Rationale
      The SQL spent 100% of its database time on CPU, I/O and Cluster waits. 
      This part of database time may be improved by the SQL Tuning Advisor.
   Rationale
      Database time for this SQL was divided as follows: 100% for SQL 
      execution, 0% for parsing, 0% for PL/SQL execution and 0% for Java 
      execution.
   Rationale
      SQL statement with SQL_ID "517a9chpzmptq" was executed 2134 times and 
      had an average elapsed time of 0.53 seconds.
   Rationale
      Top level calls to execute the SELECT statement with SQL_ID 
      "a4jz2cwj2g8uy" are responsible for 100% of the database time spent on 
      the SELECT statement with SQL_ID "517a9chpzmptq".
      Related Object
         SQL statement with SQL_ID a4jz2cwj2g8uy.
         select id, name, durchfuehrung, beschreibung, serie, 
         decode(calc_days.next_termin(serie),durchfuehrung, 
         calc_days.next_termin(serie,2), calc_days.next_termin(serie)) ntm 
         from adm_sched_param where aktiv<>0 and operatingsystem = 'W7$2' 
         order by durchfuehrung asc,fix4robot desc,name

Finding 2: CPU Usage
Impact is 1.66 active sessions, 32.41% of total activity.
---------------------------------------------------------
Host CPU was a bottleneck and the instance was consuming 89% of the host CPU. 
All wait times will be inflated by wait for CPU.
Host CPU consumption was 89%.
 
   Recommendation 1: Application Analysis
   Estimated benefit is 4.64 active sessions, 90.47% of total activity.
   --------------------------------------------------------------------
   Action
      Look at the "Top SQL Statements" finding for SQL statements consuming 
      significant time on CPU. For example, the SELECT statement with SQL_ID 
      "bf0b1kf434ff9" is responsible for 15% of CPU usage during the analysis 
      period.
 
   Recommendation 2: Host Configuration
   Estimated benefit is 1.66 active sessions, 32.41% of total activity.
   --------------------------------------------------------------------
   Action
      Consider adding more CPUs to the host or adding instances serving the 
      database on other hosts.
   Action
      Session CPU consumption was throttled by the Oracle Resource Manager. 
      Consider revising the resource plan that was active during the analysis 
      period.
 
 
Finding 3: "User I/O" wait Class
Impact is .4 active sessions, 7.77% of total activity.
------------------------------------------------------
Wait class "User I/O" was consuming significant database time.
Waits for I/O to temporary tablespaces were not consuming significant database 
time.
The throughput of the I/O subsystem was not significantly lower than expected.
 
   No recommendations are available.
 
 
Finding 4: Session Connect and Disconnect
Impact is .26 active sessions, 5.01% of total activity.
-------------------------------------------------------
Session connect and disconnect calls were consuming significant database time.
 
   Recommendation 1: Application Analysis
   Estimated benefit is .26 active sessions, 5.01% of total activity.
   ------------------------------------------------------------------
   Action
      Investigate application logic for possible reduction of connect and 
      disconnect calls. For example, you might use a connection pool scheme in 
      the middle tier.
 
 
Finding 5: Undersized SGA
Impact is .13 active sessions, 2.44% of total activity.
-------------------------------------------------------
The SGA was inadequately sized, causing additional I/O or hard parses.
The value of parameter "sga_target" was "20480 M" during the analysis period.
 
   Recommendation 1: Database Configuration
   Estimated benefit is .11 active sessions, 2.11% of total activity.
   ------------------------------------------------------------------
   Action
      Increase the size of the SGA by setting the parameter "sga_target" to 
      23040 M.
 
   Symptoms That Led to the Finding:
   ---------------------------------
      Wait class "User I/O" was consuming significant database time.
      Impact is .4 active sessions, 7.77% of total activity.

Outlier Summary - Cell Level

  • Outliers are cells whose average performance is outside the normal range, where normal range is -/+ 1 standard deviation
  • Outlier cells must have a mininum of 10 IOPs. Idle cells are not considered for outlier analysis.
  • Outliers for hard disks are displayed when Hard Disk IOPs exceeds 102.24 (1% of maximum capacity of 10,224)
  • Outliers for flash disks are displayed when Flash Disk IOPs exceeds 13645.76 (1% of maximum capacity of 1,364,576)
  • A 'v' and a dark yellow background indicates an outlier value below the low range
  • A '^' and a light red background indicates an outlier value above the high range
  • A '*' and a dark red background indicates over maximum capacity
  • Disk Type <F|H>/<size>: F-Flash, H-Hard Disk
  • Maximum cell capacity for hard disks: IOPS: H/12.5T: 2,556 | IO MB/s: H/12.5T: 1,776
  • Maximum cell capacity for flash disks: IOPS: F/5.8T: 341,144 | IO MB/s: F/5.8T: 25,000
  • There are no cell outliers on flash
  • There are no cell outliers on hard disks

Exadata Cell Server IO MB/s Statistics - Outlier Cells

  • These statistics are collected by the cells and are not restricted to this database or instance
  • Outliers are cells whose average performance is outside the normal range, where normal range is -/+ 1 standard deviation
  • Outlier cells must have a mininum of 10 IOPs. Idle cells are not considered for outlier analysis.
  • Outliers for small reads, small writes, large read, large writes, must have a minimum of 10 requests for the corresponding small read, small write, large read, large write statistic.
  • Outliers for hard disks are displayed when Hard Disk IOPs exceeds 102.24 (1% of maximum capacity of 10,224)
  • Outliers for flash disks are displayed when Flash Disk IOPs exceeds 13645.76 (1% of maximum capacity of 1,364,576)

  • A '^' and a light red background indicates an outlier value above the high range

  • These statistics are collected by the cells and are not restricted to this database or instance
  • Storage Index - bytes saved by storage index and percentage of requested bytes saved by storage index
  • Flash Cache - bytes read from flash cache and percentage of requested bytes read from flash cache
  • Offload - bytes processed by the cells and not returned to the database
  • Passthru - bytes returned as-is to the database (for reasons other than high cell cpu) and percentage of requested bytes returned as-is to the database
  • Reverse Offload - bytes returned as-is to the database due to high cell cpu and percentage of requested bytes returned as-is to the database
